<div id="review_1386785372" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1386785372" />
    <a title="Diana" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10971036-diana"><img alt="Diana" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1478630291p2/10971036.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1386785372?book_show_action=true">Sep 08, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Diana" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Diana" href="/user/show/10971036-diana">Diana</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780486421247" href="/book/show/42210.Life_Is_a_Dream">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1386785372" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4549935688655101247">*read in parallel the original version by Calderón de la Barca and the English translation provided by <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/1804382.Michael_Kidd' title='Michael Kidd' rel='nofollow noopener'>Michael Kidd</a><br/>*the quotes will be in English<br/><br/><i>Given that life is so short, let&apos;s dream, my soul, let&apos;s dream!</i><br/>Play about the choices we have in life, the good and the bad in it, destiny, change, honour, present. It lit in me the flame of fighting and of living. <br/><br/><i>As a woman, I come to move you to the cause of my honour; as a man, I come to encourage you to recover your crown. As woman, I come to beg y</i></span>
  <span id="freeText4549935688655101247" style="display:none">*read in parallel the original version by Calderón de la Barca and the English translation provided by <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/1804382.Michael_Kidd" title="Michael Kidd" rel="nofollow noopener">Michael Kidd</a><br />*the quotes will be in English<br /><br /><i>Given that life is so short, let's dream, my soul, let's dream!</i><br />Play about the choices we have in life, the good and the bad in it, destiny, change, honour, present. It lit in me the flame of fighting and of living. <br /><br /><i>As a woman, I come to move you to the cause of my honour; as a man, I come to encourage you to recover your crown. As woman, I come to beg your sympathy by throwing myself at your feet;; as a man, I come to serve you by aiding your soldiers. As a woman, I come to request your support in my dishonor and anguish; as a man, I come to support you with my sword and character. And finally, consider that if you try to seduce me today as a woman, as a man I will slay you in legitimate defense of my honour; for in restoring my good name I must act as a lovesick woman to plead for help and as a man to win respect.</i> - Rosaura<br />I found this passage to be an evidence to gender fluidity in the play (Rosaura also pretended to be a man in the beginning) that could also be read in a feminist matter. The double-standards are exposed, the ideas that only men could win their honour back and fight and that women can only make themselves miserable and <b>beg</b> for honour and pardon are fought.<br /><br /><br /><u>Favourite character</u>: Rosaura<br /><u>Favourite quote</u>: <i>The rich man dreams of more riches, which only bring him more worries; the poor man dreams that he suffers in misery and poverty; the man who improves his lot dreams; the man who toils and petitions dreams; the man insults and offends dreams. And in the world, in short, everyone dreams who he is although no one realizes it. I dream that I'm here, weighed down by these chains, and I've dreamt that I found myself in more flattering circumstances. What is life? A frenzy. What is life? A vain hope, a shadow, a fiction. The greatest good is fleeting, for all life is a dream and even dreams are but dreams.</i><br /><u>Favourite scene</u>: the beginning of the play, when Rosaura finds Segismundo chained<br /><br />An amazing read! </span>
  <a data-text-id="4549935688655101247" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


