<div id="review_2304078190" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2304078190" />
    <a title="Quiver" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9310150-quiver"><img alt="Quiver" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1489326638p2/9310150.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2304078190?book_show_action=true">Apr 11, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Quiver" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Quiver" href="/user/show/9310150-quiver">Quiver</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/18905406-life-is-a-dream">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9310150-quiver?shelf=a-english">a-english</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9310150-quiver?shelf=p-poetry-plays">p-poetry-plays</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9310150-quiver?shelf=in-translation-esp-por">in-translation-esp-por</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2304078190" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10582705818300448319">I stumbled across this play when looking for quotes relating <em>life </em>and <em>dream</em>. I found it on Gutenberg, read the first few pages, and thereafter I was charmed.<br/><br/>Sigismund is Prince and heir to the throne of Poland. It is prophesied that he will have a violent, cruel nature and is therefore imprisoned by his father, the King, in a tower where he grows up under a caretakers guidance. The play begins when Sigismund is a young man, and the King decides to test Sigismund&apos;s nature by letting him into the </span>
  <span id="freeText10582705818300448319" style="display:none">I stumbled across this play when looking for quotes relating <em>life </em>and <em>dream</em>. I found it on Gutenberg, read the first few pages, and thereafter I was charmed.<br /><br />Sigismund is Prince and heir to the throne of Poland. It is prophesied that he will have a violent, cruel nature and is therefore imprisoned by his father, the King, in a tower where he grows up under a caretakers guidance. The play begins when Sigismund is a young man, and the King decides to test Sigismund's nature by letting him into the palace and explaining the situation. The King threatens that if Sigismund does not behave these new luxurious surroundings and his princely heritage will all turn out to be but a dream.<br /><br />Drama ensues.<br /><blockquote>What is life? 'Tis but a madness.<br />What is life? A thing that seems,<br />A mirage that falsely gleams,<br />Phantom joy, delusive rest,<br />Since is life a dream at best,<br />And even dreams themselves are dreams.<br /><br />(Sigismund's soliloquy)</blockquote><br /><br />Certain themes stood out:<br /> <br /> 	 Most obvious and tied to the title: Life is a dream and dreams are life and we should be careful how we behave in either. <br /><br /> 	 Cliched but present: Forgiveness  leads to forgiveness (while bile to bile). <br /><br /> 	 A feminist aspect: Rosaura used to be the betrothed of Astolfo, a pretendent to the throne, during his time in Muscovy and before his arrival to Poland. The first scene opens with her finding Sigismund in his prison, as she seeks entrance to the Polish court to avenge herself on Astolfo, and she remains the second most important character of the play if not the most important. She is determined, resourceful, will dress as a man if this helps her cause, but will ask a man for help too; she is cunning and self-sufficient. An unexpectedly strong character I enjoyed as a counterpoint to Sigismund's weakness and volatility. <br /> <br /><br />Overall, an enjoyable take on the duality of the dream world and the waking world, with much plot besides.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10582705818300448319" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

